@greypilgrim228​​⁠ starting a group to bring awareness to slavery is still better than nothing. The issue with the subplot is that it never really gets expanded upon. By the end of the series, elf slavery is still perfectly legal, which goes against the “all was well” quote the caps the series off. No one seems to take the slavery seriously at all besides Hermione. 
It’s brushed off as a goofy joke critiquing Hermione, but when the issue is slavery, (no matter how ingrained slavery is to the elves’ minds, since elves like Dobby can still be abused legally and want to be free, it’s still a massive issue) it doesn’t fit the tone. It would be better if it was so that Dobby was an exception, and that house elves by law are free and are just happy workers (most elves in the series are happy enough, but they’re not allowed to stop working unless their master says so). Hermione would just be ignorant because the only elf she knows about is Dobby, so she could assume all elves are treated like that, and then she could learn that elves are legally free, but then STILL goes on about it for a while because she couldn’t admit she was wrong. That would be more tonally consistent and the make the other characters seem like less of an asshole for not caring about slavery.

TL;DR: elf slavery bad and Hermione was still better about it than most of the other characters in the subplot who didn’t give a flying shit about the slavery, no matter how annoying she was.

@ScottishGremlin My view on the house elves is that they're meant to be a commentary on house wives/trad wives, not slaves. It's a lot less iffy and fits a lot better if you view it as, 'the house wives' like it, they don't want to be freed. And some house elves (wives), like Dobby, are abused and beaten and so when they're free they're happy and want pay and holidays etc. whereas Winky was happy, if a bit used (also, she wasn't just a servant, she was also a confidant for Crouch and a carer for his son, much more like an actual housewife), and so when she was 'freed', she was miserable. 

Career driven, progressive Hermione, having personal beef with all these house elves (wives) being treated like this, fits better, and their annoyance when she insists they're slaves, and need paying, works better because when women were starting to get more rights, there was a lot of discourse and scorn between women who still wanted to be house wives, and women who wanted to have careers (which still exists of course).

It's still a commentary on slavery, but I think it fits better if it's not House Elves=Slaves, but rather, House Elves=House/Trad Wives=slaves.

